# Mastra AI Basic Design Principles

## Core Architecture
- Agents are capability containers (tools + instructions); they never control flow
- Workflows own all orchestration, control flow, and state management
- Steps are atomic, stateless execution units with clear input/output schemas
- Tools are single-purpose functions that do one thing well

## Separation of Concerns
- Tools execute actions
- Agents coordinate tools with AI reasoning
- Steps wrap executables with validation
- Workflows orchestrate steps with control flow

## Control Flow Rules
- All loops, recursion, and retries belong in workflows
- All branching and conditional logic belongs in workflows  
- All suspension and resumption belongs in workflows
- Agents only decide HOW to use tools, never WHEN to execute

## State Management
- Steps must be stateless pure functions
- Agents are stateless; they process and return
- Workflows manage all state and execution context
- Use Zod schemas for all input/output validation

## Decision Framework
- Needs loops or recursion? → Use a workflow
- Needs branching or conditions? → Use a workflow
- Needs to wait or suspend? → Use a workflow
- Needs LLM reasoning? → Use an agent (as a step)
- Transforms data? → Use a step
- Single focused action? → Use a tool

## Anti-Patterns
- Never implement recursion in agents
- Never put control flow in agent instructions
- Never maintain state in steps
- Never mix orchestration with capability